Full Description: Remodelista is an online design site to help those who are remodeling, building or just looking for the right piece to improve their home.  Corporate background Remodelista was founded as an independent website in 2007 by Carlson, Connolly, Hall, and Lonsdale to provide an online sourcebook for users planning a home renovation or remodel with the goal of furnishing rooms with a mix of classics, vintage finds and modernist pieces. In 2008, Josh Groves joined as publisher and CEO. Remodelista was acquired by San Francisco company SAY Media in August 2011. In 2012, Remodelista launched Gardenista.com with former New York Times columnist Michelle Slatalla as editor-in-chief. In 2015, Carlson and Groves (using Remodelista, LLC) bought Remodelista and Gardenista from SAY Media for an undisclosed amount. In May 2016, Remodelista and Gardenista were acquired by Realtor.com, operated by the News Corporation subsidiary Move, Inc..  In November 2017, Remodelista launched The Organized Home (www.organized-home.com) in conjunction with the publication of the book "Remodelista: The Organized Home." In May 2019, Realtor.com sold the three sites back to Remodelista, LLC operated by Carlson and Groves.

Full Description: Audio Impressions creates high definition sample libraries backed by music technology for composers working under deadlines. Its primary objective is to create sample libraries that deliver the performance and sound of live musicians in ways that have been overlooked. Audio Impressions has created multiple new technologies to enable composers to create mock-ups of live orchestration that actually translate directly to fully accurate and playable scores. These technologies include DVZ, a real-time subtractive polyphony process that divides notes into their proper sections just as occurs in a live performance; SPACE, a first Decca Tree and spot microphone cross-bleed simulation process that transforms individually recorded instruments into a single live performance; and DVZ Libraries, which are comprised of sounds that Audio Impressions sampled at studios around the globe, recorded at 192 kHz with high quality microphones, preamps, and no consoles. Audio Impressions was launched in 2004 and is based in Los Angeles, C.A.

It is co-funded by the European Commission as an Integrated Project under the Seventh Framework Programme for research and development (FP7). The project aims to provide a platform for a European-led early global consensus on fundamental questions connected to the development of the future mobile and wireless communications system, and pave the way for future standardization. METIS 2020 is a consortium of 29 partners coordinated by Ericsson, which includes manufacturers, network telecommunications operators, academic institutions, automotive industry, and a research center. METIS 2020‚Äôs timeline is from November 1, 2012, to April 30, 2015.

Description: MacConnect is the oldest and largest Mac-centric ISP on the planet today.
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Established in 1996 during the early days of the Internet explosion, MacConnect is the oldest and largest Mac-centric ISP on the planet today.  The service was born in a time when Mac users were generally treated as second class citizens online.  MacConnect stepped in to fill the need for an Internet Service Provider focused on the unique needs of Mac users. Our first service was basic dial-up service at 28.8 Kbps,  which was then upgraded to a blazing fast (in 1997 terms) 56 Kbps.  We naturally provided email service with every account, and offered the added benefit of a Mac-centric online community complete with custom client software (Telefinder BBS, for those that might remember). Every MacConnect customer was afforded free space for personal web pages on our WebSTAR servers.  This soon spawned requests to host business and professional web sites, and our Velocity hosting service was born.  Originally operated on a single T-1 connection on a set of PowerMac 9600s in our office in Northport, New York, the service grew rapidly forcing our first move into carrier grade telecommunications space in Melville, New York. By 1998 we‚Äôd outgrown that space too, so we packed our bags and relocated the operation to a major datacenter in the northern Virginia area.  This afforded us the space, power and network resources to offer Mac server co-location and we were soon responsible for racks and racks full of beige and Bondi blue G3s. Through the years there were several more moves and upgrades, and some organizational and management changes as the service continued to grow and mature.  In 2005 the MacConnect was moved to a datacenter on Long Island owned and operated by MacConnect‚Äôs original founder, who took the service full circle by re-purchasing it in 2006. In 2010 MacConnect is still going full steam ahead, with Mac-centric hosting and co-location our primary services.  We‚Äôre proud to say that we still have many customers that have been with us for 10 years or more with no indications that they‚Äôre looking to leave.  We believe that this is a testament to the level of service we‚Äôve provided in the past and will be providing well into the future. While we‚Äôre blowing our own horns, we‚Äôll also let you in on a little secret.  We can‚Äôt name names, but we‚Äôre very proud to say that several of our Mac-centric competitors actually operate out of our datacenter on our network.  Our service is so good, that even our competitors become our customers!
